I’ve fixed the substantive standard before implementation: the binary crime attribute has only one comparison, so changing its baseline must reverse the sign but cannot change the magnitude. The baseline-invariant corrected MMs are 0.626 for less crime and 0.374 for more crime (25.1-point spread), the largest point-estimated within-attribute spread, but only slightly above commuting time (23.7 points). The defensible claim is therefore a large, robust crime contrast—not proven unique dominance. Housing Cost will demonstrate genuine multi-level reparameterization.
